(ii) was in respect of a patentable invention developed and/or discovered while Dr Gray was an employee of the University; 
(iii) did not disclose the interest of the University; and 
(iv) constituted a dealing with personal property to which the University was entitled.

Paragraph 171A of the Sirtex defence, incorporated by reference into the cross-claim, alleged that if Dr Gray knew of various matters pleaded in the statement of claim then in the premises pleaded in paragraphs 162 to 171A of the defence he was:
(i) in a position where his duties to Sirtex at law, in equity and pursuant to ss 232(2), 232(4), 242(6), (1000)(1)(b) and/or (c) and 1002G(1) of the Corporations Law of Western Australia were in conflict with his personal interests and/or his duties to CRI; and (ii) acting in breach of those duties and provisions; and (iii) further or alternatively, acting in fraud of Sirtex;
to secure the benefits to himself or further or alternatively CRI of acquiring and/or maintaining ownership of shares in Sirtex being a company in which NJI had covenanted to subscribe, and/or NJI and others subscribe, moneys for the development of the acquired inventions the benefit of which accrued to Dr Gray and CRI in proportion to their respective shareholdings from time to time, in Sirtex.

They included the following: 

 (i) a particulate material having a diameter in the range of from 5 to 200 microns comprising a polymeric matrix and stably incorporated radionuclide; 

 (ii) the particulate material according to claim 1 wherein the radionuclide is incorporated by precipitation; 

 Claims 3 to 5 covered the particulate material wherein the polymeric matrix is partially cross linked, comprises 1% to 20% cross linking, and alternatively comprises about 4% cross linking.

They included the following: 

 (i) a controlled release preparation comprising an ionic polymer matrix loaded with an active compound being complexed with a complexing agent to modify the release of the active compound from the polymer matrix;

 (ii) a preparation according to claim 1 wherein the ionic polymer matrix is in the form of microspheres;

 (iii) a preparation according to claim 2 wherein the microspheres have a diameter in the size range of 10-200 micron, preferably in the size range of 20-70 micron.
